@article{Katz2010a,
abstract = {Geochemical analyses of the carbonate tests calcified by foraminifera have provided much of the foundation for reconstructions of past ocean and climate conditions, and for chemostratigraphy. In particular, reconstructions of climate history (including temperature, salinity, and ice volume), ocean paleocirculation patterns, the carbon cycle, paleoproductivity, marine carbonate chemistry, and chemostratigraphy have relied on measurements of isotopic and trace element composition of foraminiferal calcium carbonate, and variations in these geochemical records through time and space. Substantial work has been done on details of traditional proxies (e.g., $\delta$18O, $\delta$13C) and on emerging proxies (e.g., $\delta$11B, $\epsilon$Nd) in recent years; hence, a new overview of these proxies provides a timely reference and educational tool. We review the geochemical proxies that utilize foraminiferal carbonate tests, including potential uses of the proxies for reconstructions through time: $\delta$18O, $\delta$13C, trace elements (Mg, Cd, Ba, Zn, B, U), 87Sr/86Sr, $\delta$26Mg, $\delta$11B, and $\epsilon$Nd. Both planktic and benthic foraminifera are included; planktic foraminifera provide information on the upper few hundred meters of the surface ocean, whereas benthic foraminifera provide information on conditions at the seafloor and in shallow porewaters, from shallow seas to deep ocean basins.},
annote = {Geochemical proxies 
Uses: study climate history (temp, salinity, ice volume); ocean paleocirculation patterns; the carbon cycle; paleoproductivity; marine carbonate chemistry

Benthic foraminifera. Sea floor surface; most abundant in upper 1cm of sediment (epifaunal microhabitat); may live as deep as 20 cm (infaunal microhabitat); may also reside attached to sea grass and coral.

Planktic foraminifera. Certain species correlated with cooler or warmer water temp. Single species dominates at poles. Need to know preferred habitat depth/seasonality to interpret geochemical signals in their tests. There are shallow, intermediate/thermocline, and deep dwelling planktic foraminifera. Nutrients are scarce near the surface so many shallow species bear photosynthetic symbionts.

del{\_}w and del18O (isotope ratio deviation from standard for seawater and the calcium tests, respectively): water with a 16O isotope is evaporated more readily than 18O. Precip over land is 16O-enriched {\textgreater} glacial ice is enriched and {\textgreater} river runoff to oceans is enriched. For every 1 degree C increase in temp, there's a decrease in the measured del18Ocalcite value. (Because more 16O is released from ice sheets?)

16O preferentially evaporates (and falls as precip on land and ice caps). So, when the average global temp is warmer, more ice cap volume melts into the sea (and maybe there's more river runoff? Not sure how that would work out in a water balance), and the ocean collects more O16, creating a lower seawater del18O ratio that's recorded in calcite tests.

Along the same logic, there's a relationship between the del18O of seawater and global sea levels. (likely varies through time as ice sheet del18O varies).

Carbon fractionation processes: photosythesis (large); carbonate precip (small)},
